eath, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Kilbride, County Meath, Irland","Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Irland"},"nl":{"Abt 1344–Deceased":"circa 1344–Overleden","1348–Female":"1348–Overleden","1370–1398":"1370–1398","1344–Male":"1344–Overleden","1348":"1348","Abt 1344":"circa 1344","1344":"1344","1398":"1398","1370":"1370","Kilbride, County Meath, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Kilbride, County Meath, Ierland","Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Ierland"},"en":{"Abt 1344–Deceased":"about 1344–Deceased","1348–Female":"1348–Deceased","1370–1398":"1370–1398","1344–Male":"1344–Deceased","1348":"1348","Abt 1344":"about 1344","1344":"1344","1398":"1398","1370":"1370","Kilbride, County Meath, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Kilbride, County Meath, Ireland","Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rochford,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Niall.","English: variant of   Ratchford  .","Irish: of Norman origin, probably brought to Ireland by the Normans after 1171, when Henry II acquired Dublin. However, it is not known if it was an English name (see   Ratchford  ), or a Norman equivalent of the French name   Rochefort  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rockford","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Rochford   or   Ratchford  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Rachford","meanings":["English:","variant of   Rochford  .","variant of<b>Rackford</b>, a habitational name from Rackenford in Devon,recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Racheneforda</i>, which Millsinterprets as ‘ford suitable for riding, by a stretch of river’."]},{"name":"Ratchford","meanings":["habitational name from Rochford (Worcestershire), from Old English <i>ræcc</i> ‘hunting dog’ (genitive <i>ræcces</i>) + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","habitational name from Rochford (Essex). Early forms of the name ending in <i>Ro-</i> suggest that the placename derives from Old English <i>hrōc</i> ‘rook’ or the Old English personal name <i>Hrōc(a)</i> + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, but the 13th century forms in <i>Ra-</i> and <i>Re-</i> suggest that the first element is Old English <i>ræcc</i> ‘hunting dog’.","English:"]},{"name":"Rotchford","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Caitlin.","Irish and English: variant of   Rochford  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Nicholas Rochford, Knight was born about 1344, in Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Ireland. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. Sir Nicholas Rockford Knight. He died in Kilbride, County Meath, Ireland."},"et":{"Abt 1344–Deceased":"umbes 1344–Surnud","1348–Female":"1348–Surnud","1370–1398":"1370–1398","